Shakespeare’s use of language in the play creates a dramatic and exciting atmosphere. In this extract, Macduff is
horried at nding Duncan’s body. His language shows how awful Duncan’s death is, and how it has affected him.

In this extract, Shakespeare uses language to make the atmosphere dramatic and
exciting. Macduff has just discovered Duncan’s body; as the audience never sees the
body, Shakespeare uses Macduff’s reaction to convey how horric the murder was.
Macduff’s language shows how shocked and horried he is, which adds drama to the
scene. Lennox and Macbeth both ask questions, which add to the tension and (in
Macbeth’s case) provide dramatic irony. Shakespeare also uses language to create
drama elsewhere in the play. For example, violent imagery and commands build
tension during the confrontation between Macbeth and Macduff in Act 5, Scene 8.

Macduff’s distress at nding Duncan’s body is clear from the language he uses. He speaks in
short, exclamatory sentences, which makes him sound panicked and upset. This increases the
pace of the dialogue and adds to the excitement of the scene. Shakespeare uses exclamations
such as “Murder and treason!” to make the language disjointed, which reects Macduff’s
thoughts at this moment. He is so shocked by the discovery that he cannot control his speech.
This is further highlighted by his statement that “Confusion now hath made his masterpiece”
and by Macbeth and Lennox’s questions that he cannot answer. When Macduff says “Do not
bid me speak”, Shakespeare shows Macduff’s absolute “horror” at what he has seen. This is
reinforced by the repetition of the word “horror”, which adds to the drama of the scene.

and speaks in short sentences. He uses a lot of exclamations, which makes his language dramatic.
